data.content:
Here are the three breaking changes and fixes:

---

**1. Buffer.cs — `[InlineArray]` no longer allowed on `record struct` (C# 13)**

`record struct` synthesizes methods incompatible with inline arrays. Change to a plain `struct`:

```csharp
[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]
struct Buffer
{
    private int _element0;
}
```

---

**2. Generator.cs — `stackalloc` in local functions inside iterators is now an error**

C# 13 closes the loophole that allowed `stackalloc` in local functions within iterator methods. Extract it to a regular static method:

```csharp
unsafe class DataGenerator
{
    IEnumerable<int> Generate()
    {
        yield return 1;
        Process();
    }

    static void Process()
    {
        int* p = stackalloc int[10];
        // ... work with pointer
    }
}
```

---

**3. Resolver.cs — Collection expression `[]` overload resolution changed**

C# 13 considers `params ReadOnlySpan<T>` and `params Span<T>` overloads during resolution. The empty collection `[]` now matches `ReadOnlySpan<int>`, making the call ambiguous or silently changing which overload is picked. Fix by being explicit:

```csharp
class Resolver
{
    static void Process(ReadOnlySpan<int> ros) {}
    static void Process(Span<object> s) {}

    static void Main()
    {
        Process(ReadOnlySpan<int>.Empty);  // explicit target type
    }
}
```

---

**Summary of patterns:**

| File | C# 13 breaking change | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Buffer.cs | `[InlineArray]` banned on `record struct` | Use plain `struct` |
| Generator.cs | `stackalloc` banned in iterator local functions | Move to a regular method |
| Resolver.cs | New `params` span overload resolution | Add explicit type cast |
